{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2goncharova_ver03/data/sn83045462/00280605244/1949010901/0445.xml":{"full_text":"W\\t J&unday ^laf\nWith Doily Evening Edition.\nWASHINGTON. D. C.\nPublished by\nThe Evening Star Newspaper Company.\nFLEMING NEWBOLD, President.\nB. M. McKELWAY, Editor.\nMAIN OFFICE: 11th St. and Pennsylvania Ave.\nNEW YORK OFFICE: 110 East 42d St.\nCHICAGO OFFICE) 435 North Michigan Ave.\nDelivered by Carrier\u2014Metropolitan Area.\nDaily and Sunday Daily Onl'< Sunday Only\nMonthly ..1.20* Monthly -90c 10c per copy\nWeekly 30c Weekly 20c 10c per copy\n*!0e additional when 5 Sundays are in a month.\nAlso 10c additional for Night Flnol Edition In those\nsections where delivery is made.\nRates by Mail\u2014Payable in Advance.\nAnywhere in United States.\nEvening and Sunday Evening Sunday\n1 month 1.50 1 month 90c 1 month 60c\n6 months.. 7.50 6 months 5.00 6 months 3.00\n1 year _15.00 1 year 10.00 1 year 6.00\nTelephone Sterling 5000.\nEntered at the Post Office, Washington, D. C.,\nas second-class mail matter.\nMember at the Associated Press.\nThe Associated Press is entitled exclusively to the use\nfor republication of all the local news printed in this\nnewspaper, as well as all A. P. news dispatches.\nC\u20144 SUNDAY, January 9, 1949\n.\u2014\u2014\u2014!W\nMore Efficient Appropriating\nRepresentative Clarence Cannon of\nMissouri, slated to resume his position as\nchairman of the Appropriations Commit\ntee, is reported to have under consideration\na number of changes in subcommittees\nand their procedure. One of these, if it\nbecame effective, would be a boon to the\nDistrict of Columbia.\nThe proposal contemplates having all\nthe subcommittees each of which is\ncharged with detailed handling of one or\nmore appropriation bills\u2014meet separately\nbut at the same time so that their reports\nwould be available and ready for, kouse\naction early in the session. If a successful\nplan could be devised and put into opera\ntion there would be less likelihood of\nend-of-session congestion on appropriation\nbills. The proposal might be considered as\na step toward Senator Byrd\u2019s plan for an\nomnibus appropriation bill. If workable\nIn other respects, it would also strengthen\nthe practical operation of the so-called\nbudget ceiling law, under which Congress\nis supposed to estimate income and outgo\nfor the ensuing fiscal year by February 15.\nThere would be peculiar advantages to\nthe District of Columbia if such a reform\nbecame effective. Many of our financial\ndifficulties result from the fact that the\nlocal appropriation bill so often gets\ncaught in adjournment jams because of\ndelayed consideration in the House. Fur\nthermore, the District Legislative Commit\ntees, which must shape revenue measure^,\nare inclined to wait for the appropriation\nbill to show how much money is required.\nAnd in the 80th Congress there was a\nstalemate for several weeks, with the Ap\npropriations Subcommittee waiting for a\ntax bill from the Legislative Committee,\nand the Legislative Committee waiting for\naction on the appropriation bill. The re\nsult was that the delayed tax bill never\ngot through the Senate and the local\nsalary increase provision wa^, on that\naccount* eliminated at the last minute\nfrom the bill which authorized it.\nIf the local appropriation bill received\napproval in the House early in the session,\nthe revenue-raising legislation would be\nan appropriate companion measure. It\nIs to be hoped that Mr. Cannon\u2019s commit\ntee may be able to improve procedure in\nthis respect. While it would require other\namendment of the rules, The Star suggests\nagain that local appropriations and legis\nlation be handled by a Joint Committee\non the District of Columbia. With such a\ncommittee considering both income and\noutgo for the District at the same time, we\ndoubtless would obtain a better balanced\nfinancial structure; certainly we would be\nspared the illogical procedure of one\ncommittee functioning independently in\nrunning up more expenses than the Ap\npropriations Committee can meet with\nthe available dollars.\nTightening Up on Security\nThere is no area of government in which\ngtricter safeguards against espionage and\neareless leakage of information are war\nranted than in the realm of atomic energy\nresearch. This is a field in which the\nUnited States largely has a monopoly of\nInformation, particularly with regard to\nthe atomic bomb. Such being the case, it\nIs natural to suppose that every possible\neffort ahd device will be used by our\npotential enemies to learn what is gping\non behind our atomic \u201ciron curtain.\u201d\nIt is against this background that the\nAtomic Energy Commission\u2019s latest rules\nto tighten up on security of atomic secrets\nmust be viewed. The eighteen considera\ntions by which security risks are to be\njudged are more drastic than the list of\nrules which guide loyalty officials of the\nregular departments, but few persons are\nlikely to contend that they are not neces\nsary. The commission lists nine classes of\nderogatory information against an em\nploye which would \u201cestablish a presump\ntion of security risk\u201d and nine more that\nwould subject him to suspicion. The\nstandards will apply also to the employe\u2019s\nor prospective employe\u2019s spouse. The final\ndecision in any case will be issued only\nafter an \u201cover-all. common-sense judg\nment, made after consideration of all the\nrelevant information,\u201d the commission\nstates.\nThe commission has espoused an Im\nportant principle in preparing its guide\nbook on security clearances. This is that,\nin the last analysis, the commission\nmust balance the cost to the program of\nnot having any individual\u2019s services\nagainst \u201cany possible risks involved\u201d in\nhaving him on the payroll. But the rules\nmake it plain that the commission will\nnot imperil the whole atomic program\nby retaining the services of any person\nwhose connections or activities placed him\nin the security risk category. This is a\nreasonable precaution that should be\nrigidly adhered to.\nMeanwhile, the Federal Loyalty Review\nBoard also has tightened up on security\nrestrictions affecting civil service employes\nin general. The latest ruling makes it\nmandatory for department heads to dis\nmiss employes holding membership in the\nCommunist Party, the Communist Political\nAssociation or the Young Communist\nLeague. It will surprise many persons to\nlearn that heretofore such membership\nhas been regarded as only one factor to\nbe considered In determining the loyalty\nof a suspected employe. There is abundant\nevidence to show that Communists have\ndivided loyalties. The board is right in\nholding that no person who divides his\nallegiance between the United States and\nRussia has a right to be an employe of\nthe Government.\nDean Acheson\nGiven the fact that the condition of his\nhealth has made General Marshall\u2019s re\ntirement imperative, the President could\nhardly have chosen a more experienced\nman for Secretary of State than Dean\nAcheson. Because of Mr. Acheson\u2019s past\nassociation with Alger Hiss, who has been\nindicted for perjury in connection with\ncharges having to do with a Communist\nspy ring, the selection has been greeted\nwith coolness in some quarters. There can\nbe little doubt, however, that the Senate,\nwhen it studies and acts upon the appoint\nment, will approve it readily enough.\nThis is so for the simple reason that\nMr. Acheson\u2019s record is in itself powerful\nevidence of his fitness for the office to\nwhich he has been called by the President.\nTo begin with, he knows the State Depart\nment inside out, having served there with\ngreat distinction from 1941 until his re\ntirement as Undersecretary in June of 1947.\nDuring those years of service, often in the\nrole of Acting Secretary, he consistently\ndisplayed vigor and intelligence of excep\ntional value to Secretary Byrnes and later\nto Secretary Marshall.\nAn international lawyer of outstanding\nability, Mr. Acheson has already con\ntributed a great deal to the formulation of\nsome of the most basic elements of our\nforeign policy in both the economic and\ndiplomatic fields. Former Assistant Secre\ntary of State Adolf Berle has been quoted\nas telling the House Un-American Activities\nCommittee that the Secretary-designate,\nduring the height of the war in 1944, was\nin the department\u2019s pro-Russian wing and\nonce vouched for Mr. Hiss. That may well\nbe. In those days, many excellent Amer\nicans, eager to speed up victory and hoping\nfor a new era of international co-operation,\nwere inclined to cater to the Soviet Union,\nwhose long-term intentions were not then\nclear. As for vouching for Mr. Hiss\u2014whose\nculpability, incidentally, has not yet been\ndefinitely established\u2014it is worth noting\nthat Mr. Acheson was in a large company,\nincluding distinguished Republicans like\nJohn Foster Dulles.\nIn any case, whatever may have been his\nfeelings in 1944, Mr. Acheson, by no stretch\nof the imagination, can be accurately de\nscribed as favoring a soft or appeasing\npolicy toward Russia now. For one thing,\nin 1946, he headed the State Department\ncommittee that drafted the essentials of\nthe American plan for international atomic\ncontrol\u2014a plan bitterly opposed by Moscow.\nSimilarly, early in 1947, he was the first\nof our high officials to speak out bluntly\nagainst the Soviet Union\u2019s \u201caggressive and\nexpanding\u201d policy\u2014a statement that drew\na sharp formal protest from Foreign Min\nister Molotov.\nAgain, later in the same year, Mr. Ache-\nson helped formulate the Greek-Turkish\naid project to check the Red tide in that\npart of the world, and a month before\nSecretary Marshall\u2019s famous Harvard\naddress on the subject, he outlined the\nEuropean Recovery Program in a speech\nat Cleveland, Mississippi. Finally, just two\nweeks before his retirement, he went to\nWesleyan University in Connecticut and\ngave voice to the most scathing official\nindictment of Russia heard up to that time\nin the postwar world.\nThis record speaks for itself. As Secre\ntary of State, Mr. Acheson is not likely to\nbe foolishly anti-Soviet just for the sake\nof being anti-Soviet, but it is obvious, if\nhis past performance may be taken at face\nvalue, that he will not be soft either. Our\nforeign policy, as President Truman has\nemphasized, is not facing a change. The\nState Department will be in competent\nhands under Mr. Acheson's direction.\nCyprus: Much-Coveted Isle\nAnother claimant to much-coveted\nCyprus is making its voice heard. The\nclaimant is Turkish nationalism, expressed,\nnot officially, but by the Turkish press and\nuniversity student demonstrations. Inter\nestingly enough, the claim is a contingent\none. These Turkish nationalists do not\ndemand that Britain, the present possessor\nof Cyprus, yield the island forthwith to\nTurkey. What they ask is that, if Britain\ndoes leave Cyprus, it shall be restored to\nTurkey rather than be bestowed upon\nGreece, which has long aspired to incor\nporate it with the Greek national domain.\nRivalry over Cyprus is nothing new, be\ncause since the dawn of history it has been\nfought over repeatedly and possessed by\nmany masters. Its desirability is explained\nby its location. This long, wedge-shaped\nisland lies in the bight of sea where the\nEastern Mediterranean makes a sharp bend\nbetween Asia Minor and \u00a3>Vria. The only\nisland in that region, it is the strategic\nkey to the entire region, especially in the\nair age.\nBritain\u2019s possession of Cyprus dates from\nthe great international crisis of the late\n1870s, when the British government of the\nday backed Turkey against a victorious\nczarist Russia which threatened to domi\nnate the whole Near East. The Turkish\nSultan leased Cyprus to the British so that\nthey might have an effective base for their\nfleets and armies if an Anglo-Russian war\nover Turkey should break out. This lease\nhold status lasted until World War I, when\nTurkey joined the central powers and was\nthus involved in war with Britain and its i\nallies. Thereupon Britain annexed Cyprus\nas an integral part of its empire. And the\nvalue of Cyprus for Britain has grown with\nthe loss of former British bases in Egypt,\nPalestine and elsewhere in the Near and\nMiddle East.\nHowever, Britain\u2019s Imperial Interests\nhave been increasingly challenged by the\nnationalistic desires of a majority of the\nCyprus population. Cyprus was partly\ncolonized by Greeks in ancient times, and\nGreek blood, language and culture were\naccentuated under the dominion of Rome\nand its Hellenized successor, the medieval\nByzantine Empire. On the breakup of that\nempire, Cyprus passed briefly to the Ve\nnetians and then to the Turks, who con\nqitred it toward the end of the sixteenth\ncentury and held it until the lease to\nBritain three centuries later. Those cen\nturies of Turkish rule have left their mark\nin a Mohammedan minority which num\nbers about one-fifth of a total population\no$ some 400,000. Whatever their origin, the\nCypriot Moslems feel themselves to be\nTurks and strongly oppose the aim of the\nGreek-feeling majority to unite Cyprus\nwith Greece itself. This has led the Moslem\nelement to back the British and combat\nGreek nationalist agitation.\nOne other curious factor should be noted\nin this complex situation. The small but\nactive Communist Party in Cyprus, though\ncomposed almost wholly of Greek-speaking\npersons, has recently abandoned its sup\nport of union with Greece and now de\nmands independence. That probably is\nbecause the Cypriot \u201ccomrades\u201d no longer\nbelieve that Greece is likely soon to fall\nunder Communist control.\nOf course, all these aspirations are rather\nacademic because Britain has no inten\ntion of quitting Cyprus. The British gov\nernment recently made this clear in an\nemphatic statement of policy. And every\nthing indicates that Cyprus will remain\nthe chief bastion of British power in the\nEastern Mediterranean.\nMr. Bullitt's Report\nWilliam C. Bullitt\u2019s testimony before the\nJoint Senate-House Committee on Foreign\nEconomic Co-operation makes grim read\ning. Just returned from an investigatory\nmission to China as the committee's special\nemissary, he recommends virtually all-out\naid to the forces still under the command\nof Generalissimo Chiang Kai-shek as the\nonly way to avert not only a Communist\nconquest of the whole of China but also\nan eventual Communist sweep throughout\nmost of Asia, with ultimately disastrous\nconsequences to the entire non-Communist\nworld, including ourselves.\nThis thesis represents a point of view\nlong held, not only by Mr. Bullitt but also\nby other qualified observers of Asiatic\naffairs, including some high officers in our\narmed forces. It appears, however, to be\na minority view, not shared by the ad\nministration and not backed by the bulk\nof American public opinion. As seen in\nthis country, Chiang Kai-shek and his\nregime are fatally undermined and dis\ncredited. The logical conclusion is, there\nfore, that \u201caid\u201d to Chiang, in the accepted\nmeaning of that word, would come too late.\nImplementation of the Bullitt policy would\nsignify American intervention in China\non a huge scale and our inevitable involve\nment in the civil war. Aside from the\npolitico-diplomatic possibilities, this would\nrequire vast expenditures in money and\nmaterials which could not be made on top\nof our present foreign commitments unless\nthe country were placed on virtually a\nwar footing, with greatly increased taxa\ntion and imposition of drastic controls over\nour economic life.\nThere is nothing to indicate that either\nthe administration or the new Democratic\ndominated Congress believes that such\nemergency measures are either necessary\nor practicable. Certainly, public opinion\nwould balk strenuously at the prospect of\nthe attendant sacrifices unless our official\nspokesmen declared them vital to our\nnational security. Thus, whatever else\nmay be said of it, the Bullitt report is not\n\u201cpractical politics.\u201d\nOf course, if Mr. Bullitt and those who\nshare his views are correct in their ap\npraisal, almost no sacrifices would be too\ngreat to avert the catastrophe he envis\nages. Therefore, the hope is that his dark\npredictions will not materialize.\nRussia's War Prisoners\nThe parallel notes sent by Britain,\nFrance and the United States to the Soviet\ngovernment on the matter of German war\nprisoners put the spotlight on one of\nthe least savory aspects of the postwar\nperiod.\nThe status of war prisoners has long\nbeen defined and regulated by interna\ntional agreements among most civilized\nnations. These agreements provide for\ntheir humane treatment during their war\ncaptivity and their release and repatria\ntion soon after the close of hostilities.\nUnfortunately, these provisions were not\nuniformly observed by the victors in World\nWar II. The chief obstacle was Soviet\nRussia, which was not a signatory to some\nof the agreements and desired to retain\nwar prisoners to repair some of the dam\nage they had done on Soviet soil. In Rus\nsian eyes, this was logical, since the forced\nlabor of Its own citizens Is a common prac\ntice In the Soviet Union. With Russia bent\non this action, Britain and France re\nsolved to retain their respective quotas of\nwar prisoners, both nations being faced\nwith an acute man-power shortage. And\nthis practice was followed by several of the\nminor victors.\nThe number of German war prisoners\nwas unprecedentedly enormous. The total\nat the war's close exceeded 8.000,000. This\nwas because the Nazi regime had mobilized\nvirtually the entire adult male population\nin its last-ditch resistance. And it was\nestimated that almost half of these had\nfallen into Russian hands.\nAt the Potsdam Conference held shortly\nafter the end of hostilities in the spring of\n1945, the victors could come to no agree\nment as to the extent to which German\nwar prisoners could be employed virtually\nas slave laborers. The one point on which\nthey all agreed was the fixing of January 1,\n1949, as the time limit beyond which no\nwar prisoners were to be held except those\ncharged with or convicted of war crimes.\nThis agreement has been lived up to by\nall the signatories except Soviet Russia\nand Poland. Russia has been consistently\nevasive and uncommunicative regarding\nthe status and number of German war\nprisoners in its hands. In the spring of\n1947, Foreign Minister Molotov stated that\nRussia still held nearly 900,000, though\nthat figure was generally regarded as a\ngross understatement. At any rate, though\nthe Soviet news agency has just declared\nthat the \u201coverwhelming majority\u2019\u2019 have\nbeen repatriated and that the rest will be\nsent home during this year, it would\nappear that nearly 500,000 acknowledged\nGerman war prisoners remain in Russian\ncustody, the estimated number held in\nPoland running between 40,000 and 60,000.\nNeither government has ever permitted in\nspection by the International Red Cross,\nas the Western Powers have done.\nThe Anglo-French-American notes\u2014\nwhich do not cover the question of\nJapanese prisoners still in Soviet hands\u2014\ncall attention to Russia\u2019s default and ask\nthe reason for it. The hope is that this\nrepresentation will remedy one of the\nmost regrettable phases of an unfortunate\ndeparture from civilized standards of\nInternational conduct.\nSpires of the Spirit\nThe Lure of the Lovely\nThings of Good Report Are Found to Be Catching\nas Well as Things Evil\nBy the Rev. Frederick Brown Harris, D.D., Litt.D.\nThere is such a thing as the lure of the\nloathsome. Rottenness is sometimes phosphor\nescent. Even the inherently ugly, decked in\nthe unabashed livery of evil, seems strangely\nto attract, as a ser\npent charms a hum\nming bird. The grin\ning gargoyles on the\nexterior of medieval\ncathedrals suggest\nthe coronation of the\ngrotesque. In archi\ntecture, in literature,\nin life, the repulsive\noften exercises a\nstrange drawing\npower.\nThere always is the\nsubtle temptation to\nj be the one with the\nmuck-rake. Reformers, denouncing the loath\nsome, dealing with the nasty, seem never\nhappy unless they are exposing something or\nshowing up somebody. The ripening experi\nences of life bring the realization that even\nattacks against the disreputable must be\nwaged wisely, tenderly, and with tears. Paul\ncalled it, speaking the truth in love.\nThe truth is exalted mostly by exemplifica\ntion, not by negation, and anathemas. The\nmost convincing way of showing the deformi\nties of a crooked stick is to lay a straight one\nbeside it. This is not to deny that evil is con\ntagious. Badness spreads, we gloomily say, as\nthe old adage is quoted about one rotten ap\nple contaminating a whole basketful of fruit.\n\nCertain emotional diseases are highly infec\ntious. Discouragement, for instance; is there\nanything more contagious? Under its impact\npeople who were standing on their feet go\ndown like tenpins, as one defeatist rolls the\nswift and deadly balls. How quickly that at\ntitude will seep through a conference, a com\nmittee or a forum, sending the thermometer\nof morale from near boiling down to near zero!\nDefeatism stems out of fear, and fear rides off\nin a panic like wild horses. Fear is the father\nof failure. James Rqssell Lowell makes Hosea\nBigelow say, \"Folks that\u2019s afeared to fail are\nsure of failin\u2019.\u201d\nHatred is another emotion fearfully catch\ning. But equally contagious are positive emo\ntions which build up, instead of tearing down.\nCourage is highly contagious. What confirma\ntions of that are spread before us in the stir\nring postwar annals now' being read by millions!\nGoodness is the most attractive thing in all\nthis tangled, tragic world\u2014and the most\ncatching. When Pippa passes with her simple\nunspoiled goodness, all unconscious is she that\nas she sings rapturous bluebirds of happiness\nare wheeling about her and white doves of\npurity are perching on sordid casements of\nmisery and at windows of woe.\nWriting to the Emperor Trajan, Pliny called\nChristianity \u201cthat contagious superstition.\" But\nthat \u201ccontagion\u201d is the most beautiful thing\nthat has found its setting on this spinning\nisland in the skies. Bishop Berggrav, in whom\nthe lure of the lovely was made flesh, so\nradiated goodness that during his imprison\nment the Nazi guards were frequently changed\nfor fear of the contagion of his spirit.\nIn the midst of all that is loathsome on this\nplanet, the Sermon on the Mount blazes like\na bouquet of diamonds\u2014more admired than\nacquired, more highly assessed than possessed\nand practiced. Goodness, wherever found, like\nthe first fragrant arbutus beneath the rotted\nleaves, as spring trips north, is the most fas\ncinating and winsome thing on earth. It is\nthe delicate fragrance of life. It is the lilting\npoetry of existence. It is the crowning acme\nof all true joy. Alas, when the lovely comes\nknocking at our hearts in vain! Always, what\nwe see depends not so much on where we\nstand as on what we are. bur character masters\nour eyes and declares our affinities\u2014which\nipeans, in ourselves is the loathsome or the\nlovely.\nOne passage above all the headmaster of one\nof the great schools of America loved to read,\nas the hundreds of boys assembled in the long,\nvaulted study hall each day for morning\nprayers. Those boys, now helping to bear the\nresponsibilities and burdens of the world,\nhave carried ever in their memories the sound\nof his never-forgotten voice: \u201cFinally, breth\nren,\" he read, \u201cwhatsoever things are true,\nwhatsoever things are honest, whatsoever\nthings are just, whatsoever things are pure,\nwhatsoever things are lovely, whatsoever things\nare of good report\u2014\u201d the deep-toned voice\nwould pause an instant, and then go on to\nleave the final, lingering accent in one climac\ntic word\u2014\u201cif there be any virtue, and If there\nbe any praise, think on these things.\u201d\nDuring this Janus-faced month, with its\nlong echoes of the Roman god, looking in two\ndirections at once, it is vital to remember that*\nthere is the lovely and the loathsome bidding\nfor our eyes, and that: \u201cAs a man thinketh in\nhis heart, so is he.\u201d\nT 1 Some Shadows of Coming Events\ni^ooRing /\\neaa A re Noted Here atld Abroad\n(By the World Staff of the Associated Press.)\nArrangements for President Truman\u2019s Inaug\nuration and the festivities connected with it\nare touching off a series of feuds among promi\nnent persons, especially those in the entertain\nment world. Backstage pushing and shoving\n1 for invitations to the inaugural ball and for\nprominent places on the gala program of en\ntertainment the night before is terrific. (Both\nthese functions are unofficial A member of\nthe Inaugural Committee says one orchestra\nleader enlisted the backing of a dozen Senators\nand Representatives \u201cand practically every\u2019\nmember of the cabinet except Marshall.\u201d but\nstill couldn't wangle a spot for himself on the\nprogram. The Hollywood invitation list, largely\nin the hands of Actor Melvyn Douglas, husband\nof Representative Helen Gahagan Douglas,\nDemocrat, of California, is fairly broad, this\ncommitteeman said, \u201cand even includes some\nRepublicans.\u201d But the shrieks of those left off\ncan be heard all the way from Sunset boulevard\nto Pennsylvania avenue.\nBuilding Outlook\nNEW YORK.\u2014Signs of a slower year in real\nestate and building are accumulating: The\nPrudential Insurance Co. has announced it\nwill build no more low-rental housing because\nof building costs. Projects planned by some\nother insurance companies and savings banks\nhave been postponed for the same reason. The\nBureau of Labor Statistics and the Department\nof Commerce predict a general drop of 4 to 5\nper cent in volume. A reduction in residential\nvalues to about .40 per cent above prewar is\nI predicted in the current issue of the Review of\nthe Society of Residential Appraisers.\n\u201cRecession*\nAre we entering a recession? That depends\non what you mean by recession. The word may\nmean: 1. A mere receding of business activity\nfrom a higher level. 2. A bad slump, somewhat\nless than a depression but nevertheless bringing\nmass unemployment and so forth. Under the\nfirst meaning, yes, the United States is experi\nencing a recession. Prices and jobs apparently\nhave turned slightly downward although they\nare still sky-high compared to levels for years\npast. But in the sinister meaning of a half\ngrown depression, the country is not entering\na recession in the opinion of Government offi\ncials and most economists. They say business\nactivity is likely to stay at very high levels\nthroughout 1949.\nPalsky-Walsky\nBERLIN.\u2014Col. Prank Howley, American sec\ntor commandant, issued his ban on fraternizing\nwith Russians after one of his subordinates took\na Soviet officer home for Christmas dinner.\nGenerally speaking, the order has no practical\neffect because the Russians almost never\nfraternize anyway.\nIncome Taxes\nThere\u2019s no point in delaying your 1948 income\ntax return with the idea that tax rates may\nbe changed\u2014in fact, most income taxpayers\nwill be better off if they make their returns\nright away, iThey\u2019re not actually due until\nMarch 15.i Pour out of five income taxpayers\nwill get refunds on 1948 overpayments. The\nGovernment operates on a \u201cfirst come, first\nserved\" basis in making refunds. Even if rates\nare changed, taxes due on 1948 income won\u2019t\nbe affected.\nTammany\nNEW YORK\u2014In an attempt to regain power,\nTammany Hall is modernizing what it acknowl\nedges fundamentally the old Thanksgiving\nparty and Christmas basket. It is hiring a paid\nsocial worker to take charge of the \u201chelping\nhand\u201d activity that always made voter friends\nfor the Manhattan Democratic organization.\nReciprocal Trade\nIt looks like one of the first major acts of\nthe new Congress will be to erase the law,\npassed by the Republican-controlled 80th Con\ngress, that the administration contends has\n\u201chamstrung\u201d the reciprocal trade law. Under\nthe Reciprocal Trade Act adopted in 1935 the\nSecretary of State, under the President's super\nvision, could reduce tariffs against other nations\nthat lowered their own trade barriers. The\n80th Congress continued the act to July 1,\n1949, but required that if the Federal Tariff\n1 Comm Vision advised against a certain reduc\ntion, and the President decided to put it into\neffect anyway, he would have to inform Con\ngress why.\nBritain-Palestine\nLONDON.\u2014Some diplomats here see a pos\nsible change in Britain's Palestine policy in\nthe transfer of Palestine Expert, Haroid Beeley\nfrom a Foreign Office desk to the past of\ncounselor to the British Embassy at Copen\nhagen. Denmark. Mr. Beeley has been accused\nby some newspapers of being strongly pro-Arab.\nNazi Secrets\n\nLONDON.\u2014The first two volumes of German\nForeign Office documents captured by the\nAllies are to be published in the spring. The\ndocument* relate the Third Reich's interna\ntional dealings up to 1939.\nFifty Years Ago\nThe Star for January 2, 1899, told of the\nreplacement of the flag of Spain by that of the\n_ United States in the capital\nAmerican Flag of Cuba the previous day. A\nIn Havana formal transfer of sovere\nignty had been arranged and\nwas carried through as planned. \"When Gen.\nCastellanous left the palace with his staff,\nthe companies of the Leon Eattalion had\nalready defiled through the cordon of Amer\nican troops and gone on board their transport.\nThe American troops saluted him. Gen.\nClous and Capt. Hart, as representatives of\nthe American commission, walked on either\nside, his staff following. A narrow street runs\nfrom the Plaza of Arms to Caballeria wharf. A\nSpanish girl on a balcony of one of the houses\nalong this street displayed a Spanish flag and\ncried: \u2018Viva Espana! Viva el capitan general!\u2019\nIn an instant Castellanous and his staff were\nsobbing. It was an extraordinary scene. Their\ngrief was respected While these things\nwere happening the American flag was raised\nover the wreck of the Maine, a few hundred\nfeet away.\u201d\nFollowing the war with Spain there had\nbeen much talk about the poor quality of food\nfurnished American troops in\nNo Chemicals Cuba and elsewhere, and it\n(jsecj commonly was charged that\nchemicals had been used in\nthe preparation of canned beef. The Star of\nJanuary 3, 1899, however, printed communi\ncations from the three largest packers\ncategorically denying this complaint. People\nof all classes, they declared, had used their\nbeef products for a quarter of a century with\nout complaint. The packers raised the question:\nWhy should anybody think that they had\nemployed chemicals as preservative agents?\nTheir meat, they argued, was cooked very\nmuch as it would be in private homes and then\nsealed in airtight cans in which it would re\nmain good until opened. The packers invited\nthe public to visit their plants and see for\nthemselves how meat was processed.\nThe Associated Press having asked former\nPresident Grover Cleveland for an expression\nof his opinion, the 22d and\nCleveland Against 24th Chief Executive re\nExpansion plied, as quoted in The\nStar for January 5, 1899:\n\"I do not care to repeat my views concerning\nthe prevailing epidemic of imperialism and\nterritorial expansion. 'Assuming, however, that\nmy views on the subject are antiquated and\nunsuited to these progressive days, it is a matter\nof surprise to me that the refusal of certain\nnatives of our n<jw possessions to acquiesce in\nthe beneficence of subjecting them to our con\ntrol and management should in the least dis\nturb our expansionists. The remedy is\nobvious and simple. The misguided inhabi\ntants of our annexed territory who prefer\nsomething different from the plan for their\ncontrol which we propose or who oppose oyr\ndesigns in their behalf should be slaughtered.\nThe killing of natives has been a feature of\nexpansion since expansion began.\u201d\n\nThe Fifty Years Ago column last Sunday re\nferred to the death of Senator Justin B.\nMorrill, December 28, 1898, but\nCorrection erroneously credited him to Maine 1\nrather than his native Vermont. This-mistake\narose from confusion with a distinguished\ncontemporary. Lot Myrick Morrill, who was in\nfact a Senator from Maine during part of the\nlong period served by Juttin Morrill.\nOpposes Repeal of U. S.\nBan on Closed Shop\nCourt Ruling Cited to Show Union\nGains Without Monopoly\nBy Gerard P. Reilly\nAlthough the decision of the Supreme Court\nupholding the validity of State statutes for*\nbidding closed shop and union shop contracts\ncame as no surprise to the bar, the thorough\ngoing analysis which the problem received in\nthe opinion of Mr. Justice Black and the con\ncurring opinion of Mr. Justice Frankfurter\nmakes the holding an important landmark in\nthe field of labor law. It may also have a far\ni reaching effect in shaping congressional atti\ntudes on the revision of the Taft-Hartley Act.\nThe unanimity of these two justices, who\nare frequently at odds on constitutional ques\ntions, reveals thjt the court today, having\nthrown away such past obstacles to social\nreform as the Lochner and Adkins cases, in\nwhich \u201cthe old\" court struck down legislation\nregulating hours of employment and fixing\nminimum wages as repugnant to the due\nprocess clause, is prepared to take a consistent\nhands-off policy on attempts by the States to\nregulate the excesses of labor unions. Tins\nmeans that the States will continue as im\nportant laboratories for experiment in the\nexplosive area of industrial relations.\nThe test cases presented to the court were\nconcerned wuth the North Carolina, Nebraska\nand Arizona statutes. Twelve other States,\nhowever, also prohibit any form of compulsory\nunion membership contracts. It is clear from\nthe reasoning of the court that the validity of\nall these statutes has been lifted from the\nrealm of debate.\nAt the recent interstate conference on labor\nlegislation sponsored by the Labor Department\nshortly after the election, union delegates an\nnounced a drive to induce the Legislatures of\nthese 15 States to repeal such enactments.\nThe success of this campaign is dubious, how\never, as most of these States are predominantly\nagricultural Moreover, the disputed laws in\nmany instances were adopted pursuant to\npopular referenda which members of the State\nLegislatures can hardly disregard.\nThe real hope of the unions, therefore, Is in\nlimiting the application of these laws to\npurely local industries by persuading Congress\nto pre-empt the field of legislation in fac\ntories, mines and transportation companies,\nthe operation of which affects interstate com\nmerce. Under the Taft-Hartley Act the States\nare given a free hand even in these industries\non the question of placing restraints on com\npulsory union membership. Although the Fed\neral law permits the union shop with certain\nrestrictions, It contains a provision authorizing\nStates and territories to prohibit the enforce\nment of agreements which require member\nship in a labor organization as a condition of\nemployment.\nOf course, if unions are able to put over ths\nextreme program of repealing the Taft-Hartley\nlaw and restoring the Wagner Act in advance\nof substitute legislation, this provision also\nwill fall. There is a real question, however, as\nto whether such action by Congress standing\nalone would narrow the breadth of the State\nstatutes.\nThe Senate committee which reported th#\nWagner Act in 1935 disclaimed any Intent to\nlegalize or extend the closed shop in juris\ndictions in W'hich it was illegal. And it would\nseem that this expression of congressional in\ntent would govern judicial interpretation of\nany revived Wagner Act should the application\nof these State laws again be drawn into ques\ntion.\nThis would indicate that union* officials\nwould have to secure special legislation which\nwould give greater legal standing to closed\nshop agreements than the Wagner Act did in\norder to attain their objective. Members of\nCongress who retain some independence of\nthought on labor matters, however, may well\nquestion the fairness or wisdom of any such\nproposal in the light of certain comments of\nthe court.\nThe main theme of both the Black and\nFrankfurter opinions was that the considera\ntions urged against the anticlosed-shop laws\nwere matters which lay within the discretion\nof the legislators rather than the judges. But\nbecause the organizations challenging the\nstatutes had invoked the equal-protection and\ndue-process clauses, the court found it neces\nsary to point out the justification for the policy\nof the legislation.\nMr. Justice Black in his opinion remarked:\n\u201cBecause the outlawed contracts are a\nuseful incentive to the growth of union\nmembership, it is said that these laws\nweaken the bargaining power of unions and\ncorrespondingly strengthen the power of\nemployers. This may be true, but there are\nother matters to be considered. State laws\nalso make it impossible for an employer to\nmake contracts with company unions which\nobligate the employer to refuse jobs to union\nmembers. This circumstance alone\nis sufficient to support the State laws against\nthe charge that they deny equal protection\nto unions as against employes and nonunion\nworkers.\u201d\n\nHe then went on to point out that at one\ntime many companies required employes to\nsign agreements stating that they would not\nbecome labor union members and that such\nanti-union practices became so obnoxious that\nState and Federal laws were passed to ban\ndiscrimination against union members and to\nout'aw yellow-dog contracts. Reciting the\nSupreme Court cases which had held the legis\nlative attempts to curb such practices uncon\nstitutional, he emphasized that in recent years\nthose cases had been overruled, thus releasing\nCongress and State Legislatures from a judi\ncial strait jacket.\n\u201cAppellants now ask us to return, at least\nin part, to the due-process philosophy that\nhas been deliberately discarded, claiming\nthat the Federal Constitution itself affords\nprotection for union members against dis\ncrimination. they nevertheless assert that\nthe same Constitution forbids a State from\nproviding the same protection for nonunion\nmembers. Just as we have held that the\ndue-process clause erects no obstacle to\nblock legislative protection of union mem\nbers, we now held that legislative protection\ncan be afforded nonunion workers.\"\nIn his concurrence, Mr. Justice Frankfurter\nquoted statistics to show that total union\nmembership in this country is now 33 times\nwhat it was 50 years ago and that since the\nFirst World War the ratio of organized to\nunorganized workers has changed from 1-9 to\nalmost 1-3. Accordingly, he said that the status\nof unionism in 1948 precludes \u201cconstitutional\ncondemnation of a legislative judgment, what\never we may think of it, and that the need of\nthis type of regulation outweighs its detri\nments.\u201d He noted that under the Railway\nLabor Act the railroad brotherhods have held\ntheir own despite the congressional prohibi\ntion of union security.\nHis opinion also includes an interesting sum\nmary of the views of the late Mr. Justice\nBrandeis, whose famous dissenting opinion in\nthe Bedford Stonecutters\u2019 case aroused con\ngressional sentiment which found its expres\nsion in the passage of the Norris-La Guardia\nAct. Despite Brandeis\u2019 sympathy for trade\nunions, however, he was opposed to the closed\nshop. In a letter to Lincoln Steffens, which\nwas discovered among his papers, he wrote:\n\"But the American people should not and\nwill not accept unionism if it involves the\nclosed shop. They will not consent to the\nexchange of the tyranny of the employer\nfor the tyfanny of the employes.\" i","height":"31512","width":"22324"}}
